LOCATION:355 N. Eagleson Avenue - Room Number: 1060
SUMMARY:Spring 2026 Colloquium Series with Andrés León Araya
DESCRIPTION:The Center for Latin American and Caribbean Studies is proud 
 to present the continuation of its Colloquium Series for Spring 2026.  We
  welcome Dr. Andrés León Araya as he presents Soldier of Fortune and th
 e Landscapes of Pacification in Central America  &#160\;  Abstract: This 
 presentation examines how Soldier of Fortune (SOF) magazine constructed a
  "counterinsurgent geography" during the Central American conflicts of th
 e 1980s. By reframing local struggles as vital frontlines in a global ant
 i-communist crusade\, SOF utilized a revived "domino theory" to flatten c
 omplex regional realities into a singular geopolitical battlefield. This 
 geographic reimagining drew direct parallels between the landscapes of Ce
 ntral America and previous "lost" counterinsurgent wars in Vietnam and Rh
 odesia. Moving beyond rhetoric through "hardcore participatory journalism
 \," the magazine's staff actively intervened in these conflicts—trainin
 g Contra units in Nicaragua and overhauling weapons inventories for Salva
 doran battalions. This effort to overcome the "Vietnam Syndrome" through 
 privatized warfare established a lasting legacy\, prefiguring the modern 
 rise of Private Military Contractors (PMCs) and the persistent influence 
 of paramilitary subcultures in contemporary border and security discourse
 s.  &#160\;Andrés León Araya&#160\;is an Assistant Professor in the Dep
 artment of International Studies at Indiana University. Trained as both a
  political scientist and an anthropologist\, his work looks at the inters
 ections between plantation economies\, violence and state formation. His 
 latest book\, "The Coup and the Palm Trees: Agrarian Conflict and Politic
 al Power in Honduras" (University of Georgia Press\, 2023) interrogates t
 he Honduran present through and exploration of the country's spatiotempor
 al trajectory of agrarian change since the mid-twentieth century. Rather 
 than a case of failed democratic transition\, the book shows how the curr
 ent Honduran crisis is better understood within longer historical process
 es in which violence\, exclusion\, and dispossession became the central o
 rganization principles of the state.  Currently\, he is working on two pa
 rallel lines of inquiry. First\, the overlaps between monocrops and drug 
 trafficking in Central America. Second\, the process of pacification of C
 entral America and the continuities between the Cold War of the 1980s and
  the current "war on drugs".  &#160\;  The CLACS Spring 2026 Colloquium m
 eets Mondays from February through April\, with faculty and guest speaker
 s engaging Latin America and the Caribbean through research on history\, 
 culture\, language\, politics\, and the arts. Check the CLACS Calendar (h
 ttps://events.iu.edu/clacs/) for details.&#160\;
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p>  The Center for Latin American and Carib
 bean Studies is proud to present the continuation of its <strong>Colloqui
 um Series for Spring 2026</strong>.</p><p>  We welcome <strong>Dr. André
 s León Araya</strong> as he presents <em><strong>Soldier of Fortune and 
 the Landscapes of Pacification in Central America</strong></em></p><p>  &
 #160\;</p><p>  Abstract: This presentation examines how Soldier of Fortun
 e (SOF) magazine constructed a "counterinsurgent geography" during the Ce
 ntral American conflicts of the 1980s. By reframing local struggles as vi
 tal frontlines in a global anti-communist crusade\, SOF utilized a revive
 d "domino theory" to flatten complex regional realities into a singular g
 eopolitical battlefield. This geographic reimagining drew direct parallel
 s between the landscapes of Central America and previous "lost" counterin
 surgent wars in Vietnam and Rhodesia. Moving beyond rhetoric through "har
 dcore participatory journalism\," the magazine's staff actively intervene
 d in these conflicts—training Contra units in Nicaragua and overhauling
  weapons inventories for Salvadoran battalions. This effort to overcome t
 he "Vietnam Syndrome" through privatized warfare established a lasting le
 gacy\, prefiguring the modern rise of Private Military Contractors (PMCs)
  and the persistent influence of paramilitary subcultures in contemporary
  border and security discourses.</p><p>  &#160\;</p><p><strong>Andrés Le
 ón Araya</strong>&#160\;is an Assistant Professor in the Department of I
 nternational Studies at Indiana University. Trained as both a political s
 cientist and an anthropologist\, his work looks at the intersections betw
 een plantation economies\, violence and state formation. His latest book\
 , "The Coup and the Palm Trees: Agrarian Conflict and Political Power in 
 Honduras" (University of Georgia Press\, 2023) interrogates the Honduran 
 present through and exploration of the country's spatiotemporal trajector
 y of agrarian change since the mid-twentieth century. Rather than a case 
 of failed democratic transition\, the book shows how the current Honduran
  crisis is better understood within longer historical processes in which 
 violence\, exclusion\, and dispossession became the central organization 
 principles of the state.</p><p>  Currently\, he is working on two paralle
 l lines of inquiry. First\, the overlaps between monocrops and drug traff
 icking in Central America. Second\, the process of pacification of Centra
 l America and the continuities between the Cold War of the 1980s and the 
 current "war on drugs".</p><p>  &#160\;</p><p>  The CLACS Spring 2026 Col
 loquium meets Mondays from February through April\, with faculty and gues
 t speakers engaging Latin America and the Caribbean through research on h
 istory\, culture\, language\, politics\, and the arts. Check the <a href=
 "https://events.iu.edu/clacs/">CLACS Calendar</a> for details.&#160\;</p>
