X-SOURCE-URLS:{"IU Maurer School of Law": "https://events.iu.edu/lawiub/event/2147411-the-jerome-hall-lecture-featuring-william-baude"}
X-SOURCE-ID:iu_maurer_law
X-SOURCE:IU Maurer School of Law
DTSTART:20260311T160000Z
DTEND:20260311T170000Z
LOCATION:LOWELL E. BAIER HALL/IU MAURER SCHOOL OF LAW - Room Number: 123
GEO:39.165074;-86.526424
SUMMARY:The Jerome Hall Lecture featuring William Baude
DESCRIPTION:Beyond Tit-for-Tat  One of the most widespread constitutional
  problems today is that our constitutional norms are one-sided. We try to
  follow important rules of neutrality\, legality\, and legitimacy only to
  see others disregard them. Norms can't work this way. And so\, many of u
 s reasonably conclude\, we must engage in limited retaliation to vindicat
 e the norms we wish to see. For reasons Professor William Baude will expl
 ain\, this does not work and will not work. The only feasible solutions a
 re ones that ask a great deal more of us.  The Jerome Hall Endowed lectur
 e was established in honor Jerome Hall\, who was a pioneer in the interdi
 sciplinary analysis of legal problems. Our faculty\, and the faculty of t
 his distinguished university\, continue Hall's work through their scholar
 ship\, especially through their work with the Center for Law\, Society\, 
 and Culture.  This event has been approved for 1 hour of CLE credit by th
 e Indiana Office of Admissions and Continuing Legal Education. To attend 
 via Zoom\, register here (https://iu.zoom.us/webinar/register/WN_yrhINhfg
 TSSYDpDFMB_gNQ).&#160\;  Food is only ordered for those who RSVP.&#160\;
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p><span style="text-decoration: underline\;
 "><strong>Beyond Tit-for-Tat</strong></span></p><p>  One of the most wide
 spread constitutional problems today is that our constitutional norms are
  one-sided. We try to follow important rules of neutrality\, legality\, a
 nd legitimacy only to see others disregard them. Norms can't work this wa
 y. And so\, many of us reasonably conclude\, we must engage in limited re
 taliation to vindicate the norms we wish to see. For reasons Professor Wi
 lliam Baude will explain\, this does not work and will not work. The only
  feasible solutions are ones that ask a great deal more of us.</p><p>  Th
 e Jerome Hall Endowed lecture was established in honor Jerome Hall\, who 
 was a pioneer in the interdisciplinary analysis of legal problems. Our fa
 culty\, and the faculty of this distinguished university\, continue Hall'
 s work through their scholarship\, especially through their work with the
  Center for Law\, Society\, and Culture.</p><p>  This event has been appr
 oved for 1 hour of CLE credit by the Indiana Office of Admissions and Con
 tinuing Legal Education. To attend via Zoom\, register <a href="https://i
 u.zoom.us/webinar/register/WN_yrhINhfgTSSYDpDFMB_gNQ">here</a>.&#160\;</p
 ><p>  Food is only ordered for those who RSVP.&#160\;</p>
UID:20260311T160000Z-2147411@events.iu.edu
DTSTAMP:20251212T104923Z
URL:https://events.iu.edu/lawiub/event/2147411-the-jerome-hall-lecture-fe
 aturing-william-baude
CATEGORIES:Lectures, talks, seminars, and conferences
