BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE-URLS:{"IU Hamilton Lugar School": "https://events.iu.edu/live/events/2192804-cacr-speaker-series-talk-daricia-wilkinson-the-borde", "IU Kelley School of Business": "https://events.iu.edu/live/events/2192804-cacr-speaker-series-talk-darica-wilkinson-the", "IU Maurer School of Law": "https://events.iu.edu/live/events/2192804-cacr-speaker-series-talk-daricia-wilkinson-the-borde"}
X-SOURCE-URLS:{"IU Hamilton Lugar School": "https://events.iu.edu/live/events/2192804-cacr-speaker-series-talk-daricia-wilkinson-the-borde"}
X-SOURCE-ID:iu_hamilton_lugar
X-SOURCE:IU Hamilton Lugar School, IU Kelley School of Business, IU Maurer School of Law
DTSTART:20260312T160000Z
DTEND:20260312T170000Z
LOCATION:LOWELL E. BAIER HALL/IU MAURER SCHOOL OF LAW - Room Number: 335
GEO:39.165074;-86.526424
SUMMARY:CACR Speaker Series Talk | Daricia Wilkinson | The Borderless Nat
 ure of Online Harm: Mapping Transnational Risk Perceptions and Recourse i
 n Social and Search Systems
DESCRIPTION:Please join us for lunch while we welcome our speaker\, Daric
 ia Wilkinson\, virtually.  &#160\;Title: The Borderless Nature of Online 
 Harm: Mapping Transnational Risk Perceptions and Recourse in Social and S
 earch SystemsAbstract: This talk explores the frictions between "universa
 l" design and platform policies and the localized realities of people exp
 eriencing harm. I examine two critical dimensions: social harms\, that ma
 y be interpersonal or platform-enabled\, and algorithmic harms\, specific
 ally discussing how search algorithms in social platforms impact informat
 ion access for speakers of low-resource languages. By analyzing transnati
 onal perceptions of risk\, these studies reveal why a "one-size-fits-all"
  approach to online safety fails and highlight opportunities for cultural
 ly-attuned recourse mechanisms that empower users to seek justice in ways
  that align with their specific socio-technical environments.Bio: Daricia
  Wilkinson is an assistant professor in the Human Systems Engineering (HS
 E) program at Arizona State University and the director of the Responsibl
 e Technology and Society Lab. She is driven by a passion to build safe te
 chnology through knowledge creation about the harm that persists because 
 of AI while actively engaging in foundational research to create protecti
 ve mechanisms through design and governance. Her research interests rest 
 at the intersection of responsible artificial intelligence\, online safet
 y and human computer interaction. Dr. Wilkinson's work has been published
  in several prestigious ACM venues including CHI\, CSCW\, and RecSys. She
  was named one of the top 100 Brilliant Women in AI Ethics in 2023.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p><picture class="lw_image lw_image29805  l
 w_align_left"><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://events.iu.edu/liv
 e/image/scale/2x/gid/573/width/160/height/159/29805_wilkinson-headshot.we
 bp 2x" data-origin="responsive"/><source type="image/png" srcset="https:/
 /events.iu.edu/live/image/scale/2x/gid/573/width/160/height/159/29805_wil
 kinson-headshot.rev.1769701235.png 2x" data-origin="responsive"/><img wid
 th="160" height="159" alt="" data-alt="" data-decoration="true" src="http
 s://events.iu.edu/live/image/gid/573/width/160/height/159/29805_wilkinson
 -headshot.rev.1769701235.png" srcset="https://events.iu.edu/live/image/sc
 ale/2x/gid/573/width/160/height/159/29805_wilkinson-headshot.rev.17697012
 35.png 2x" data-max-w="345" data-max-h="342" loading="lazy" data-optimize
 d="true"/></picture></p><p><strong>Please join us for lunch while we welc
 ome our speaker\, Daricia Wilkinson\, virtually.</strong></p><p>  &#160\;
 </p><p><strong><em>Title:</em></strong> The Borderless Nature of Online H
 arm: Mapping Transnational Risk Perceptions and Recourse in Social and Se
 arch Systems</p><p><strong><em>Abstract:</em></strong> This talk explores
  the frictions between "universal" design and platform policies and the l
 ocalized realities of people experiencing harm. I examine two critical di
 mensions: <em>social harms</em>\, that may be interpersonal or platform-e
 nabled\, and <em>algorithmic harms\,</em> specifically discussing how sea
 rch algorithms in social platforms impact information access for speakers
  of low-resource languages. By analyzing transnational perceptions of ris
 k\, these studies reveal why a "one-size-fits-all" approach to online saf
 ety fails and highlight opportunities for culturally-attuned recourse mec
 hanisms that empower users to seek justice in ways that align with their 
 specific socio-technical environments.</p><p><strong><em>Bio:</em></stron
 g> Daricia Wilkinson is an assistant professor in the Human Systems Engin
 eering (HSE) program at Arizona State University and the director of the 
 Responsible Technology and Society Lab. She is driven by a passion to bui
 ld safe technology through knowledge creation about the harm that persist
 s because of AI while actively engaging in foundational research to creat
 e protective mechanisms through design and governance. Her research inter
 ests rest at the intersection of responsible artificial intelligence\, on
 line safety and human computer interaction. Dr. Wilkinson's work has been
  published in several prestigious ACM venues including CHI\, CSCW\, and R
 ecSys. She was named one of the top 100 Brilliant Women in AI Ethics in 2
 023.</p>
