BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE-URLS:{"Eskenazi Museum of Art": "https://events.iu.edu/live/events/2204193-burke-lecture-series-dr-sampada-aranke"}
X-SOURCE-ID:iu_eskenazi_museum
X-SOURCE:Eskenazi Museum of Art
DTSTART:20260327T200000Z
DTEND:20260327T210000Z
LOCATION:SIDNEY AND LOIS ESKENAZI MUSEUM OF ART - Room Number: Martin Com
 mons
GEO:39.169144;-86.519739
SUMMARY:Burke Lecture Series: Dr. Sampada Aranke
DESCRIPTION:This talk will consider the ways that famed Black American co
 nceptual artist David Hammons cites\, leverages\, and operationalizes whi
 te\, western canons to probe the generative limits of art historical disc
 ourse and canonization. The artist's intentional engagement with the prac
 tices and legacies of artists whose oeuvres have formed an avant-garde we
 stern canon like Duchamp\, Klein\, Matta-Clark\, is not about mere adorat
 ion\, but in fact a strategic assessment\, if not deformation\, of art hi
 storical discourses. Operating like a trojan horse\, Hammons has seamless
 ly created opportunities for alignment and association\, making it so tha
 t named collectors of Duchamp and museums that collect Matta-Clark have i
 ncomplete collections if they do not own a work by Hammons. This project 
 will work alongside two key Hammons works\, The Holy Bible: Old Testament
  (2002) and Days End (2021) to consider how the artist breaks disciplinar
 y canons in order to make radically renewed associations.  &#160\;  Lectu
 re will be held until 5 pm followed by questions. Reception to follow.Spo
 nsored by the Robert E. &amp\; Avis Tarrant Burke Lecture Fund.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p>  This talk will consider the ways that f
 amed Black American conceptual artist David Hammons cites\, leverages\, a
 nd operationalizes white\, western canons to probe the generative limits 
 of art historical discourse and canonization. The artist's intentional en
 gagement with the practices and legacies of artists whose oeuvres have fo
 rmed an avant-garde western canon like Duchamp\, Klein\, Matta-Clark\, is
  not about mere adoration\, but in fact a strategic assessment\, if not d
 eformation\, of art historical discourses. Operating like a trojan horse\
 , Hammons has seamlessly created opportunities for alignment and associat
 ion\, making it so that named collectors of Duchamp and museums that coll
 ect Matta-Clark have incomplete collections if they do not own a work by 
 Hammons. This project will work alongside two key Hammons works\, <em>The
  Holy Bible: Old Testament</em> (2002) and <em>Days End</em> (2021) to co
 nsider how the artist breaks disciplinary canons in order to make radical
 ly renewed associations.</p><p>  &#160\;</p><p>  Lecture will be held unt
 il 5 pm followed by questions. Reception to follow.</p><p><em>Sponsored b
 y the Robert E. &amp\; Avis Tarrant Burke Lecture Fund.</em></p>
