X-SOURCE-URLS:{"IU Hamilton Lugar School": "https://events.iu.edu/live/events/2199356-spring-2026-colloquium-series-with-beidy-sow", "IU La Casa Latino Cultural Center": "https://events.iu.edu/live/events/2199356-spring-2026-colloquium-series-with-beidy-sow"}
X-SOURCE-URLS:{"IU Hamilton Lugar School": "https://events.iu.edu/live/events/2199356-spring-2026-colloquium-series-with-beidy-sow"}
X-SOURCE-ID:iu_hamilton_lugar
X-SOURCE:IU Hamilton Lugar School, IU La Casa Latino Cultural Center
DTSTART:20260330T200000Z
DTEND:20260330T210000Z
LOCATION:355 N. Eagleson Avenue - Room Number: 2067
SUMMARY:Spring 2026 Colloquium Series with Amadou Beidy Sow
DESCRIPTION:The Center for Latin American and Caribbean Studies is proud 
 to present the continuation of its Colloquium Series for Spring 2026.  We
  welcome Dr. Beidy Sow as he presents Political Communication in Latin Am
 erica: A Case Study of Colombia  Abstract: Political communication plays 
 a crucial role in democratic processes worldwide\, and no country can aff
 ord to ignore it if it wants to ensure the proper functioning of its syst
 em. In Colombia\, political communication reflects the complexity of the 
 country's historical\, social\, and institutional dynamics\, marked by a 
 prolonged armed conflict\, deep political polarization\, and persistent i
 nequalities. This article examines the evolution of political communicati
 on in Colombia\, focusing on the interaction between political leaders an
 d citizens. It highlights the use of various channels by political leader
 s to convey their messages. The study also draws on citizen testimonies\,
  populist rhetoric\, and the different methods used by politicians to com
 municate with the population and influence their choices\, as well as the
  laws implemented to facilitate communication between leaders and their c
 onstituencies. Furthermore\, it contributes to understanding issues relat
 ed to peace processes\, social movements\, and youth participation in con
 temporary political communication practices. Overall\, the study of polit
 ical communication in Colombia will provide a better understanding of the
  profile of the country's political leaders and allow for an analysis of 
 the strengths and weaknesses of Colombian democracy.  &#160\;Amadou Beidy
  Sow is a Bamana instructor from Ségou\, Mali. Dr. Sow obtained a Master
 's degree in Second Language Teaching from the Ecole Normale Supérieure 
 in Bamako. After coming to the United States\, he earned a Master's degre
 e in International Studies at Ohio University followed by a Ph.D. in Educ
 ation (Cultural Studies in Education) with a focus on political leadershi
 p. He has published Political Leadership in the Hand of Teachers: The Typ
 e of Leadership Teacher Politicians Display on the Political Scene in Mal
 i\, VDM Verlag (2010). Dr. Sow has presented at numerous conferences. He 
 has experience teaching Bamanankan\, French\, English\, and Social Studie
 s.                  &#160\;          The CLACS Spring 2026 Colloquium mee
 ts Mondays from February through April\, with faculty and guest speakers 
 engaging Latin America and the Caribbean through research on history\, cu
 lture\, language\, politics\, and the arts. Check the CLACS Calendar (htt
 ps://events.iu.edu/clacs/) for details.&#160\;
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p>  The Center for Latin American and Carib
 bean Studies is proud to present the continuation of its <strong>Colloqui
 um Series for Spring 2026</strong>.</p><p>  We welcome <strong>Dr. Beidy 
 Sow</strong> as he presents <em><strong>Political Communication in Latin 
 America: A Case Study of Colombia</strong></em></p><p>  Abstract: Politic
 al communication plays a crucial role in democratic processes worldwide\,
  and no country can afford to ignore it if it wants to ensure the proper 
 functioning of its system. In Colombia\, political communication reflects
  the complexity of the country's historical\, social\, and institutional 
 dynamics\, marked by a prolonged armed conflict\, deep political polariza
 tion\, and persistent inequalities. This article examines the evolution o
 f political communication in Colombia\, focusing on the interaction betwe
 en political leaders and citizens. It highlights the use of various chann
 els by political leaders to convey their messages. The study also draws o
 n citizen testimonies\, populist rhetoric\, and the different methods use
 d by politicians to communicate with the population and influence their c
 hoices\, as well as the laws implemented to facilitate communication betw
 een leaders and their constituencies. Furthermore\, it contributes to und
 erstanding issues related to peace processes\, social movements\, and you
 th participation in contemporary political communication practices. Overa
 ll\, the study of political communication in Colombia will provide a bett
 er understanding of the profile of the country's political leaders and al
 low for an analysis of the strengths and weaknesses of Colombian democrac
 y.</p><p>  &#160\;</p><div class="bg-none section"><div class="row"><div 
 class="layout"><div class="text"><p><strong>Amadou Beidy Sow</strong> is 
 a Bamana instructor from Ségou\, Mali. Dr. Sow obtained a Master's degre
 e in Second Language Teaching from the Ecole Normale Supérieure in Bamak
 o. After coming to the United States\, he earned a Master's degree in Int
 ernational Studies at Ohio University followed by a Ph.D. in Education (C
 ultural Studies in Education) with a focus on political leadership. He ha
 s published <em>Political Leadership in the Hand of Teachers: The Type of
  Leadership Teacher Politicians Display on the Political Scene in Mali\, 
 VDM Verlag</em> (2010). Dr. Sow has presented at numerous conferences. He
  has experience teaching Bamanankan\, French\, English\, and Social Studi
 es.        </p><p>          &#160\;        </p></div></div></div></div><p
 >  The CLACS Spring 2026 Colloquium meets Mondays from February through A
