BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE-URLS:{"IU Kelley School of Business": "https://events.iu.edu/kelleyiub/event/2229868-kelley-teaching-seminar-oh-no-i-suspect-academic"}
X-SOURCE-ID:iu_kelley_business
X-SOURCE:IU Kelley School of Business
DTSTART:20260403T130000Z
DTEND:20260403T143000Z
LOCATION:WILLIAM J. GODFREY GRADUATE AND EXECUTIVE EDUCATION CENTER - Roo
 m Number: 3059
GEO:39.172447;-86.519399
SUMMARY:Kelley Teaching Seminar-Oh No! I Suspect Academic Misconduct – 
 What do I do?
DESCRIPTION:Faculty Panel:Russ Clark\, Sr. Lecturer\, ODT\, I-Core Co-Ord
 inator  Todd Haugh\, Assoc. Prof.\, Bus. Law &amp\; Ethics\, Faculty Liai
 son to the Office of Students Conduct  John Hill\, Clinical Prof.\, ODT\,
  Full-time MBA Chair  Lynn Keller\, Lecturer\, Bus. Law &amp\; Ethics\, C
 o-chair Academic Fairness Committee  Amy Kinser\, Teaching Prof.\, Comput
 er Skills (CPCS)\, Executive Dir. of Teaching &amp\; Learning    We have 
 all been there. A student looks a little too long at another student's wo
 rk. A student sneaks in a little help from AI. A student plagiarizes trac
 ts from the internet with no attribution. We are obligated by the univers
 ity and by ethical practice to confront suspected academic misconduct. At
  the same time\, there are clearly determined procedures that must be fol
 lowed in order to levy any form of sanctions when academic misconduct has
  been confirmed.  Working through the roiling waters of an academic misco
 nduct case can be a huge drag (in both senses of the word) on faculty\, s
 o learning how to address it can save time and heartache for everyone inv
 olved. Yes\, this seminar will be worth your time!  In this Kelley Teachi
 ng Seminar\, we will hear examples from Kelley classrooms and learn best 
 practices for dealing with suspicions of academic misconduct. In particul
 ar\, we will learn the necessary procedures and share ideas about how to 
 frame discussions with students when discussing suspicions of academic mi
 sconduct.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p>  Faculty Panel:</p><ul><li><strong>Russ 
 Clark</strong>\, Sr. Lecturer\, ODT\, I-Core Co-Ordinator  </li><li><stro
 ng>Todd Haugh</strong>\, Assoc. Prof.\, Bus. Law &amp\; Ethics\, Faculty 
 Liaison to the Office of Students Conduct  </li><li><strong>John Hill</st
 rong>\, Clinical Prof.\, ODT\, Full-time MBA Chair  </li><li><strong>Lynn
  Keller</strong>\, Lecturer\, Bus. Law &amp\; Ethics\, Co-chair Academic 
 Fairness Committee  </li><li><strong>Amy Kinser</strong>\, Teaching Prof.
 \, Computer Skills (CPCS)\, Executive Dir. of Teaching &amp\; Learning  <
 /li></ul><p>  We have all been there. A student looks a little too long a
 t another student's work. A student sneaks in a little help from AI. A st
 udent plagiarizes tracts from the internet with no attribution. We are ob
 ligated by the university and by ethical practice to confront suspected a
 cademic misconduct. At the same time\, there are clearly determined proce
 dures that must be followed in order to levy any form of sanctions when a
 cademic misconduct has been confirmed.</p><p>  Working through the roilin
 g waters of an academic misconduct case can be a huge drag (in both sense
 s of the word) on faculty\, so learning how to address it can save time a
 nd heartache for everyone involved. Yes\, this seminar will be worth your
  time!</p><p>  In this Kelley Teaching Seminar\, we will hear examples fr
 om Kelley classrooms and learn best practices for dealing with suspicions
  of academic misconduct. In particular\, we will learn the necessary proc
 edures and share ideas about how to frame discussions with students when 
 discussing suspicions of academic misconduct.</p>
UID:20260403T130000Z-2229868@events.iu.edu
DTSTAMP:20260305T145621Z
URL:https://events.iu.edu/kelleyiub/event/2229868-kelley-teaching-seminar
 -oh-no-i-suspect-academic
LAST-MODIFIED:20260306T131302Z
