DTSTART:20260408T170000Z
DTEND:20260408T180000Z
LOCATION:The Ostrom Workshop\, 513 N PARK AVE - Room Number: Tocqueville
GEO:39.171057;-86.524959
SUMMARY:Ostrom Workshop | Research Series: Paulo Ramos
DESCRIPTION:Bio  Paulo Ramos is born from the womb of his mother\, Terezi
 nha Ramos de Jesus. He is an Afro-Brazilian visual artist\, performer\, a
 ctor\, and poet whose multidisciplinarywork spans video\, performance\, a
 nd poetry. His acclaimed poetry book\, Corpos d'água\, was published in 
 2023 in Brazil. And in 2026\, the book\, titled Bodies of Water\, will be
  released in the United States\, in English\, by NP-PRESS and Counterpath
  Press. Ramos' compelling performance piece\, presented at the 12th At Fi
 rst Sigh New Works Festival Indiana University and in venues across São 
 Paulo and Tepoztlán\, gave rise to the thought-provoking videoperformanc
 e Bodies of Water: Threebuckets: a river\, a mangrow\, and a sean. Paulo 
 Ramos is a Ph.D. in Social Science in Gender and Black Studies in PUCSP. 
 Pontifícia Universidade Católica de São Paulo\,Paulo Ramos continues t
 o explore and amplify the narratives of Afro-Brazilian identity.Abstract 
  Bodies of Water is an artistic performance\, an academic confrontation g
 rounded in the studies of Denise Ferreira da Silva (2020)\, constructed t
 hrough a poetic pathway in which the body becomes theoretical expansion. 
 According to Denise Ferreira da Silva\, anticolonial art must be a confro
 ntation.  Bodies of Water: A Hybrid Cartography Flowing into an etnograph
 yWE is part of my doctoral research\, built from the memory\, orality\, a
 nd ancestry of Black women who turn their daily notes into the reinventio
 n of life in community. This reinvention constitutes their intellectual p
 roduction\, naming everything that inhabits space or emerges from the way
 s they experience the world—one that is crossed by race\, class\, and t
 he environmental. It concerns the relationship between water and Black wo
 men-mothers as a way of thinking existence\, both as a site of escape and
  of resistance.  Here\, I propose to reflect from a fieldwork perspective
  that traverses my own self—not through an autoethnographic method\, bu
 t immersed in an etnographyWE\, a new theory in development for thinking 
 about the women and the waters that came before me.  Thus\, Bodies of Wat
 er brings forth tension\, discomfort\, and a critiCREATIVE approach devel
 oped alongside my research on my grandmother\, my mother\, my aunt\, and 
 the waters—and on environmental racism (Costa 2022\; Pacheco 2012). Bod
 ies of Water is body–time–space poetry. Above all\, it is confrontati
 on. It is a profound dialogue between the Black body and water—living e
 lements\, yet constrained by the violence imposed by temporality.  Ancest
 rality and Afropessimism are both present here\, navigating together in t
 he same vessel through the currents of the Black body (Pinho 2021\; Smith
  2015)\; between these two concepts\, ecology emerges as the missing link
  that connects them.About the Ostrom Workshop Research Series  Learn abou
 t innovative research by Graduate Students and Visiting Scholars as they 
 advance the mission of the Ostrom Workshop\, building upon the theme of g
 overnance to understand and address major societal problems.
