DTSTART:20260408T210000Z
DTEND:20260408T220000Z
LOCATION:Indiana Memorial Union - Room Number: Federal Room
SUMMARY:Wiles Lecture: "A Rebellious Generation: Solidarity Activism in P
 oland and the Diaspora" with Mary Erdmans
DESCRIPTION:This talk looks at activism among political refugees from the
  Solidarność movement. The social-historical context created a politica
 l generation and radical disposition that impelled activism over time and
  space. Factors that explain activism in the diaspora include biographica
 l availability\, geographic location\, and transnational political networ
 ks.  Mary Erdmans is Professor of Sociology at Case Western Reserve Unive
 rsity. A Fulbright Scholar and past president of the Polish American Hist
 orical Association\, she authored three award-winning books: Opposite Pol
 es\, The Grasinski Girls\, and On Becoming a Teen Mom. Her articles have 
 appeared in Sociological Quarterly\, Journal of American Ethnic History\,
  and Studia Migracynjne.Reception to follow.Sponsored by the Polish Studi
 es Center with additional support from The Byrnes Institute (REEI)\, the 
 Department of Slavic and East European Languages and Cultures\, the Depar
 tment of Sociology\, and the Institute for European Studies.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p>  This talk looks at activism among polit
 ical refugees from the <i>Solidarność </i>movement. The social-historic
 al context created a political generation and radical disposition that im
 pelled activism over time and space. Factors that explain activism in the
  diaspora include biographical availability\, geographic location\, and t
 ransnational political networks.</p><p>  Mary Erdmans is Professor of Soc
 iology at Case Western Reserve University. A Fulbright Scholar and past p
 resident of the Polish American Historical Association\, she authored thr
 ee award-winning books: <i>Opposite Poles</i>\, <i>The Grasinski Girls</i
 >\, and <i>On Becoming a Teen Mom. </i>Her articles have appeared in <i>S
 ociological Quarterly\, Journal of American Ethnic History\, </i>and <i>S
 tudia Migracynjne</i>.</p><p><em>Reception to follow.</em></p><p><em>Spon
 sored by the Polish Studies Center with additional support from The Byrne
 s Institute (REEI)\, the Department of Slavic and East European Languages
  and Cultures\, the Department of Sociology\, and the Institute for Europ
 ean Studies.</em></p>
