BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE-URLS:{"IU Hamilton Lugar School": "https://events.iu.edu/hls/event/2160889-the-alchemy-of-confidence"}
X-SOURCE-ID:iu_hamilton_lugar
X-SOURCE:IU Hamilton Lugar School
DTSTART:20260421T200000Z
DTEND:20260421T213000Z
LOCATION:STEPHEN L. &amp\; CONNIE J. FERGUSON INTERNATIONAL CENTER - Room
  Number: 421/423
GEO:39.169199;-86.515674
SUMMARY:The Alchemy of Confidence
DESCRIPTION:This salon series at Indiana University features leading thin
 kers exploring how to build better digital and natural worlds.Beyond the 
 Web / After Analog Speaker Series.  Deception and honesty have long been 
 locked in evolutionary arms races. When false signals become common\, the
 y lose their power\, favoring honest signals whose reliability is enforce
 d by cost. This principle\, central to signaling theory\, explains many c
 ostly biological traits and offers insight into human communication and d
 isinformation.  This insight lies at the heart of signaling theory\, whic
 h explains many costly biological traits and behaviors once thought to be
  useless. The theory also sheds light on human culture and has become inc
 reasingly relevant for understanding disinformation and identity deceptio
 n in the digital age. However\, human reliability depends on more than co
 stly signals alone. Trust between individuals\, along with third-party en
 forcement through social bonds\, surveillance\, and institutions\, plays 
 a crucial role.  This talk explores how signaling costs\, affective trust
 \, and technological oversight interact\, with particular attention to wh
 en technologies support trust and when they undermine it. As rapid techno
 logical change reshapes the incentives for deception and detection\, unde
 rstanding the foundations of trust has never been more urgent.About the S
 peaker  Judith is a writer\, designer and artist whose work focuses on th
 e co-evolution of technology and society. She has published numerous arti
 cles about social media\, AI\, ethics and anonymity\, and is the author o
 f The Social Machine: Designs for Living Online (http://amzn.to/NXFIFt) (
 MIT Press). As the former director of the MIT Media Lab's Sociable Media 
 Group\, she and her students designed innovative interfaces for on-line c
 ommunities\; their art projects examining the future of identity\, privac
 y and mediated life have been exhibited in museums and galleries worldwid
 e.&#160\;
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p>  This salon series at Indiana University
  features leading thinkers exploring how to build better digital and natu
 ral worlds.</p><p><img src="https://vivatropolis.com/judith/JSD.CroppedSm  all.png" alt="" loading="lazy"/></p><p><strong data-olk-copy-source="Mess
 ageBody">Beyond the Web / After Analog Speaker Series.</strong></p><p dat
 a-start="131" data-end="466">  Deception and honesty have long been locke
 d in evolutionary arms races. When false signals become common\, they los
 e their power\, favoring honest signals whose reliability is enforced by 
 cost. This principle\, central to signaling theory\, explains many costly
  biological traits and offers insight into human communication and disinf
 ormation.</p><p data-start="473" data-end="771">  This insight lies at th
 e heart of signaling theory\, which explains many costly biological trait
 s and behaviors once thought to be useless. The theory also sheds light o
 n human culture and has become increasingly relevant for understanding di
 sinformation and identity deception in the digital age. However\, human r
 eliability depends on more than costly signals alone. Trust between indiv
 iduals\, along with third-party enforcement through social bonds\, survei
 llance\, and institutions\, plays a crucial role.</p><p data-start="778" 
 data-end="1319" data-is-last-node="">  This talk explores how signaling c
 osts\, affective trust\, and technological oversight interact\, with part
 icular attention to when technologies support trust and when they undermi
 ne it. As rapid technological change reshapes the incentives for deceptio
 n and detection\, understanding the foundations of trust has never been m
 ore urgent.</p><p data-start="778" data-end="1319" data-is-last-node=""><
 strong>About the Speaker</strong></p><p data-start="778" data-end="1319" 
 data-is-last-node="">  Judith is a writer\, designer and artist whose wor
 k focuses on the co-evolution of technology and society. She has publishe
 d numerous articles about social media\, AI\, ethics and anonymity\, and 
 is the author of <i><a href="http://amzn.to/NXFIFt" target="_blank" rel="
 noopener">The Social Machine: Designs for Living Online</a></i> (MIT Pres
 s). As the former director of the MIT Media Lab's Sociable Media Group\, 
 she and her students designed innovative interfaces for on-line communiti
 es\; their art projects examining the future of identity\, privacy and me
 diated life have been exhibited in museums and galleries worldwide.&#160\
 ;</p>
