BEGIN:VEVENT
X-SOURCE-URLS:{"IU Bloomington Libraries": "https://events.iu.edu/libraries/event/2193032-making-indiana-university"}
X-SOURCE-ID:iu_libraries
X-SOURCE:IU Bloomington Libraries
DTSTART:20260423T213000Z
DTEND:20260423T233000Z
LOCATION:WYLIE HOUSE (307 E. SECOND STREET)
GEO:39.161697;-86.5309
SUMMARY:Making Indiana University: A Reading\, Conversation\, and Signing
  with Jim Capshew
DESCRIPTION:Blending institutional and environmental history\, Making Ind
 iana University: History\, Landscape\, and a Sense of Place traces how th
 e university's identity has been shaped—materially and imaginatively—
 by Dunn's Woods\, the evolving campus landscape\, and the narratives thro
 ugh which generations have understood this place.  In a setting central t
 o IU's early history\, Capshew will introduce the book\, read from it\, a
 nd take questions from the audience. The event will be introduced by John
  Summerlot\, Director of Enterprise Risk &amp\; Incident Management at th
 e IU Foundation. It will conclude with a signing of a specially produced 
 booklet featuring the Wylie House chapter\, along with commemorative imag
 e cards drawn from the volume. Following the program\, guests are invited
  to enjoy a self-guided tour of the Wylie House.  Light refreshments will
  be served.  The event also celebrates IU Libraries Publishing (https://l
 ibraries.indiana.edu/libraries-publishing)\, the university's new open-ac
 cess publisher of long-form scholarly\, creative\, and public-facing work
 s. By making publications freely available worldwide at no cost to reader
 s or authors\, IU Libraries Publishing advances Indiana University's publ
 ic mission and ensures that its scholarship remains accessible to all.  T
 his event will be of particular interest to IU alumni\, Bloomington resid
 ents\, faculty and staff\, and anyone interested in university history\, 
 environmental studies\, and the evolving story of Indiana University.  Do
 ors will open at 5 p.m. This event is free and open to the public.  Free 
 parking options are available for visitors:Neighborhood Street Parking: F
 ree street parking is available after 5 p.m.\, including in areas normall
 y restricted to Neighborhood Zone permit holders.  Wylie House Museum Par
 king: Complimentary parking (no permit required) is available behind the 
 Wylie House Museum and adjacent to its Education Center (the gray barn). 
 This lot includes one accessible parking space. Access these spaces via t
 he alley behind the museum\, from Grant Street and Lincoln Street.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p>  Blending institutional and environmenta
 l history\, <em>Making Indiana University: History\, Landscape\, and a Se
 nse of Place</em> traces how the university's identity has been shaped—
 materially and imaginatively—by Dunn's Woods\, the evolving campus land
 scape\, and the narratives through which generations have understood this
  place.</p><p>  In a setting central to IU's early history\, Capshew will
  introduce the book\, read from it\, and take questions from the audience
 . The event will be introduced by John Summerlot\, Director of Enterprise
  Risk &amp\; Incident Management at the IU Foundation. It will conclude w
 ith a signing of a specially produced booklet featuring the Wylie House c
 hapter\, along with commemorative image cards drawn from the volume. Foll
 owing the program\, guests are invited to enjoy a self-guided tour of the
  Wylie House.</p><p>  Light refreshments will be served.</p><p>  The even
 t also celebrates <a href="https://libraries.indiana.edu/libraries-publis
 hing">IU Libraries Publishing</a>\, the university's new open-access publ
 isher of long-form scholarly\, creative\, and public-facing works. By mak
 ing publications freely available worldwide at no cost to readers or auth
 ors\, IU Libraries Publishing advances Indiana University's public missio
 n and ensures that its scholarship remains accessible to all.</p><p>  Thi
 s event will be of particular interest to IU alumni\, Bloomington residen
 ts\, faculty and staff\, and anyone interested in university history\, en
 vironmental studies\, and the evolving story of Indiana University.</p><p
 >  Doors will open at 5 p.m. This event is free and open to the public.</
 p><p>  Free parking options are available for visitors:</p><ul><li>Neighb
 orhood Street Parking: Free street parking is available after 5 p.m.\, in
 cluding in areas normally restricted to Neighborhood Zone permit holders.
   </li><li>Wylie House Museum Parking: Complimentary parking (no permit r
 equired) is available behind the Wylie House Museum and adjacent to its E
 ducation Center (the gray barn). This lot includes one accessible parking
  space. Access these spaces via the alley behind the museum\, from Grant 
 Street and Lincoln Street.  </li></ul>
UID:20260423T213000Z-2193032@events.iu.edu
DTSTAMP:20260129T171528Z
URL:https://events.iu.edu/libraries/event/2193032-making-indiana-university
CATEGORIES:Lectures, talks, seminars, and conferences
LAST-MODIFIED:20260305T174453Z
