X-SOURCE-URLS:{"IU Hamilton Lugar School": "https://events.iu.edu/hls/event/2212903-global-competencies-skills-development-series-early-"}
X-SOURCE-ID:iu_hamilton_lugar
X-SOURCE:IU Hamilton Lugar School, IU Kelley School of Business
DTSTART:20260501T153000Z
DTEND:20260501T163000Z
LOCATION:GLOBAL &amp\; INTERNATIONAL STUDIES BUILDING - Room Number: 1118
GEO:39.170002;-86.517492
SUMMARY:Global Competencies Skills Development Series: Early Lunch: Strat
 egic Thinking in U.S.-Africa Policy and Intelligence
DESCRIPTION:Event Description:  How do policymakers and intelligence offi
 cers navigate complex decisions in Africa and beyond?  Join Judd Devermon
 t\, former National Intelligence Officer for Africa and former Senior Dir
 ector for African Affairs at the White House\, for a live\, scenario-driv
 en session on strategy\, risk\, and global policymaking.  Devermont spent
  over a decade in the intelligence community\, advised two administration
 s\, authored the U.S. Strategy toward Sub-Saharan Africa\, and directed m
 ajor initiatives shaping billions in infrastructure\, digital connectivit
 y\, and energy investments.  This is not a lecture.  You will work throug
 h a real-world scenario: African states balancing relationships with the 
 U.S. and China while managing domestic political and development pressure
 s.  You'll assess risk\, identify second- and third-order effects\, evalu
 ate trade-offs\, and recommend a course of action.What you'll gain:      
 Insight into how intelligence and policy intersect          Frameworks to
  anticipate unintended consequences          How analysis translates into
  real-world decisions          A window into careers in intelligence\, go
 vernment\, and think tanks      Lunch will be provided. Come ready to deb
 ate\, analyze\, and defend your conclusions in an interactive\, off-the-r
 ecord setting.
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p data-start="144" data-end="168"><strong d
 ata-start="144" data-end="166">Event Description:</strong></p><p data-sta
 rt="170" data-end="266">  How do policymakers and intelligence officers n
 avigate complex decisions in Africa and beyond?</p><p data-start="268" da
 ta-end="485">  Join Judd Devermont\, former National Intelligence Officer
  for Africa and former Senior Director for African Affairs at the White H
 ouse\, for a live\, scenario-driven session on strategy\, risk\, and glob
 al policymaking.</p><p data-start="487" data-end="745">  Devermont spent 
 over a decade in the intelligence community\, advised two administrations
 \, authored the U.S. Strategy toward Sub-Saharan Africa\, and directed ma
 jor initiatives shaping billions in infrastructure\, digital connectivity
 \, and energy investments.</p><p data-start="747" data-end="771">  This i
 s not a lecture.</p><p data-start="773" data-end="943">  You will work th
 rough a real-world scenario: African states balancing relationships with 
 the U.S. and China while managing domestic political and development pres
 sures.</p><p data-start="945" data-end="1063">  You'll assess risk\, iden
 tify second- and third-order effects\, evaluate trade-offs\, and recommen
 d a course of action.</p><p data-start="1065" data-end="1088"><strong dat
 a-start="1065" data-end="1086">What you'll gain:</strong></p><ul data-sta
 rt="1089" data-end="1321"><li data-start="1089" data-end="1143"><p data-s
 tart="1091" data-end="1143">      Insight into how intelligence and polic
 y intersect    </p></li><li data-start="1144" data-end="1196"><p data-sta
 rt="1146" data-end="1196">      Frameworks to anticipate unintended conse
 quences    </p></li><li data-start="1197" data-end="1250"><p data-start="
 1199" data-end="1250">      How analysis translates into real-world decis
 ions    </p></li><li data-start="1251" data-end="1321"><p data-start="125
 3" data-end="1321">      A window into careers in intelligence\, governme
 nt\, and think tanks    </p></li></ul><p data-start="1323" data-end="1450
 ">  Lunch will be provided. Come ready to debate\, analyze\, and defend y
 our conclusions in an interactive\, off-the-record setting.</p>
